    The program crashed with EXC_BAD_ACCESS (code=2, address=0x16f603ff0) due   
    to a stack overflow, which occurred because the recursive fib function      
    lacks a base case to terminate the recursion. This caused an infinite       
    recursion, consuming all available stack space, eventually leading to a     
    memory access violation.                                                    
                                                                                
    Step-by-Step Analysis:                                                      
                                                                                
     1 Function Definition and Behavior:                                        
        • The fib function is defined as:                                       
                                                                                
           int fib(int n) {                                                     
             return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);                                        
           }                                                                    
                                                                                
          This recursive definition has no base case (i.e., no condition to     
          stop recursion when n reaches 0 or 1). As a result, it will           
          recursively call itself indefinitely for any input, such as the n =   
          100 in main().                                                        
     2 Stack Trace Analysis:                                                    
        • The stack trace shows multiple frames of fib(n) with decreasing       
          values of n: -261267, -261266, ..., all the way down.                 
        • The n value is decreasing by 1 each time, but it never reaches a      
          base case. This implies that the recursion deepens without end.       
        • The number of frames (over 260,000) far exceeds what the system       
          stack can support, resulting in a stack overflow.                     
     3 Root Cause:                                                              
        • Missing base case in recursive fib function.                          
        • The recursion never terminates, leading to infinite function calls.   
        • Stack space is exhausted, causing the program to write to invalid     
          memory (address 0x16f603ff0), hence the EXC_BAD_ACCESS error.         
     4 Value of n in Current Frame:                                             
        • Running frame variable n in the deepest frame showed n = -261267.     
        • This confirms that we are many levels deep into recursion, and the    
          input n is decreasing (n-1, n-2) without any stopping condition.      
     5 Why Not n Getting Closer to 0?                                           
        • Even though main() calls fib(100), the lack of base case means it     
          doesn’t hit fib(1) or fib(0) — instead, it keeps going: 100 → 99 →    
          98 → ... → 0 → -1 → -2 → ..., reducing indefinitely.                  
        • This infinite descent exhausts the stack.                             
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Recommendations                                                             
                                                                                
    🔧 Minimal Local Fix:                                                       
                                                                                
    Add base cases to terminate recursion.                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     int fib(int n) {                                                           
         if (n <= 1)                                                            
             return n;                                                          
         return fib(n - 1) + fib(n - 2);                                        
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This fix:                                                                   
                                                                                
     • Stops recursion when n <= 1.                                             
     • Corrects the logic of Fibonacci (fib(0)=0, fib(1)=1).                    
     • Prevents infinite recursion and stack overflow.                          
                                                                                
    🧩 More Thorough Root-Cause Fix (if needed):                                
                                                                                
     • For production code, consider memoization or iterative version to avoid  
       deep recursion entirely (especially since fib(100) is computationally    
       heavy and will overflow int).                                            
                                                                                
    Recommended Optimized Version:                                              
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <unordered_map>                                                   
                                                                                
     int fib(int n) {                                                           
         static std::unordered_map<int, int> memo;                              
         if (n <= 1)                                                            
             return n;                                                          
         if (memo.find(n) != memo.end())                                        
             return memo[n];                                                    
         return memo[n] = fib(n - 1) + fib(n - 2);                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Or, better yet, iterative:                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     int fib(int n) {                                                           
         if (n <= 1) return n;                                                  
         int a = 0, b = 1;                                                      
         for (int i = 2; i <= n; ++i) {                                         
             int temp = a + b;                                                  
             a = b;                                                             
             b = temp;                                                          
         }                                                                      
         return b;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    ✅ Summary                                                                  
                                                                                
     • Root Cause: Missing base case in recursive fib function → infinite       
       recursion → stack overflow → EXC_BAD_ACCESS.                             
     • Diagnosis: Stack trace shows never-ending recursion; variable n keeps    
       decrementing without bound.                                              
     • Minimal Fix: Add if (n <= 1) return n;.                                  
     • Thorough Fix: Use memoization or iterative approach to avoid stack       
       overflow and inefficiency.                                               
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
     1 Apply the minimal fix: Add base case if (n <= 1) return n; in the fib    
       function.                                                                
     2 Optionally, replace the recursive implementation with an iterative one   
       to avoid stack overflow and improve performance, especially for large    
       n.                                                                       
                                                                                
